          "body": "The third movement of the doxology (1:13-14) shifts to second person — *in Him, you also*. Gentile believers in Asia Minor, having heard the gospel of their salvation and believed, *were sealed in Him with the Holy Spirit of promise*. The Spirit is the *sphragis* (seal — mark of ownership, authentication, protection) and the *arrabōn* (pledge — first installment guaranteeing the rest). Both metaphors are commercial. The Spirit indwelling the believer is God's down payment on the believer's inheritance, and God does not default on down payments. Eternal security is not a theological inference here; it is a commercial-legal claim Paul makes by the chapter's vocabulary itself."
